    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-10-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-10-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="926"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d926">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Newel</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-10-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 5, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 327.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to Department instruction No. 255,
                    dated September 25, 1900, relating to the submission to arbitration of the
                    claims of certain American vessels against the Russian Government, I have the
                    honor to confirm on the overleaf my cablegram<note n="2" xml:id="d926fn2"
                        >Printed ante.</note> of this date, and in this regard to state that
                    immediately upon receipt of the instruction I communicated with the Russian
                    minister and in response thereto his excellency made an appointment with me for
                    this morning.</p>
                <p>The Russian minister informs me this morning that he has had no instructions in
                    the matter from his Government, nor has he heard anything <pb facs="0897"
                        n="799" xml:id="pg_799"/> on the subject; that he attributes this to the
                    absence of the Czar with the minister for foreign affairs from St. Petersburg,
                    that he does not feel it right for him to take any steps in the premises, but
                    that immediately upon the receipt of any instruction from his Government he will
                    advise me thereof. He does not consider it proper for him even to communicate
                    with his Government on the matter before it has communicated with him.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stanford Newel.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
